A marriage is voidable under Section 12 of the Hindu Marriage Act, 1955 (HMA), on several grounds, including: 

1. if the marriage was performed when the respondent was suffering from a mental disorder (Section 12(1)(a) HMA);
2. if the respondent was suffering from a mental illness or epilepsy at the time of the marriage (Section 12(1)(b) HMA);
3. if the respondent had a communicable venereal disease at the time of the marriage (Section 12(1)(c) HMA);
4. if the respondent was pregnant by some other person at the time of the marriage (Section 12(1)(d) HMA);
5. if the consent of the petitioner was obtained by force or fraud (Section 12(1)(e) HMA);
6. if the respondent was impotent at the time of the marriage and continued to be so until the institution of the proceedings (Section 12(1)(a) read with Section 12(2) HMA, but specifically under Section 12(1)(a) for voidable marriages due to the respondent's incapacity).

